 the FASB issued guidance on revenue recognition which requires that we recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration which we expect to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&amp;nbsp;We have performed a review of the requirements of the new revenue standard and are in the process of reviewing customer contracts and applying the &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;five&lt;/div&gt;-step model of this new guidance to each contract category we have identified and will compare the results to our current accounting practices. We plan to adopt this guidance on the &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;first&lt;/div&gt; day of our fiscal &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;2019&lt;/div&gt; year. We will likely apply the modified retrospective transition method
 which would result in an adjustment to retained earnings for the cumulative effect
 if any
 of applying the standard to contracts in process as of the adoption date. Under this method
 we would &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;not&lt;/div&gt; restate the prior financial statements presented. Therefore

 &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=display: inline; font-family:Times New Roman, Times, serif;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;the FASB issued guidance which requires an entity to measure equity investments at fair value with changes in fair value recognized in net income 
 to use the price that would be received by a seller when measuring the fair value of financial instruments for disclosure purposes
 and which eliminates the requirement to disclose the method(s) and significant assumptions used to estimate the fair value that is required to be disclosed for financial instruments measured at amortized cost on the balance sheet.&amp;nbsp; Under present guidance
 changes in fair value of equity investments available for sale are recognized in Stockholders&amp;#x2019; Equity.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;This guidance is effective for our fiscal year ended &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt; September 2019.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/div&gt;Early adoption is &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;not&lt;/div&gt; permitted. We anticipate that the adoption of this guidance on our consolidated financial statements will &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;not&lt;/div&gt; be material. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div style= font-family: Times New Roman, Times, serif; font-size: 10pt; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div style= font-size: 10pt; margin: 0pt; text-align: left; text-indent: 36pt; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(0, 0, 0);&gt;In &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt; February 2016
 &lt;/div&gt;the FASB issued guidance on lease accounting which requires that an entity recognize most leases on its balance sheet. &lt;div style=display: inline; font-family:Times New Roman, Times, serif;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;The guidance retains a dual lease accounting model for purposes of income statement recognition
 continuing the distinction between what are currently known as &amp;#x201c;capital&amp;#x201d; and &amp;#x201c;operating&amp;#x201d; leases for lessees.&amp;nbsp; This guidance is effective for our fiscal year ended &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt; September 2020.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;While we continue to evaluate the effect of adopting this guidance on our consolidated financial statements and related disclosures
 we expect our operating leases
 as disclosed in Note J &amp;#x2014; Commitments and Contingencies
 will be subject to the new standard. We will recognize right-of-use assets and operating lease liabilities on our consolidated balance sheets upon adoption

 &lt;/div&gt;the FASB issued guidance on share based compensation which requires that an entity recognize all excess tax benefits and tax&lt;div style=display: inline; font-family:Times New Roman, Times, serif;font-size:10pt;&gt; deficiencies as income tax expense or benefit in the income statement as discrete items in the reporting period in which they occur. Under current guidance
 excess tax benefits are &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=display: inline; font-family:Times New Roman, Times, serif;font-size:10pt;&gt;recognized in additional paid-in capital and tax deficiencies are recognized either as an offset to accumulated excess tax benefits

 &lt;/div&gt;the FASB issued guidance to clarify the definition of a business. The updated standard provides guidance to assist entities with evaluating when a set of transferred assets and activities is a business. Under the new guidance
 an entity &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;first&lt;/div&gt; determines whether substantially all of the fair value of the gross assets acquired is concentrated in a single identifiable asset or a group of similar identifiable assets. If this threshold is met
 the set is &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;not&lt;/div&gt; a business. If it is &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;not&lt;/div&gt; met
 the entity then evaluates whether the set meets the requirements that a business include
&lt;div style=display: inline; font-family:Times New Roman, Times, serif;font-size:10pt;&gt; at a minimum
 an input and a substantive process that together significantly contribute to the ability to create outputs. The updated guidance is effective for our fiscal year ending &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt; September 2019 &lt;/div&gt;and interim periods within that year. Early adoption is permitted

 &lt;/div&gt;the FASB issued guidance&lt;div style=display: inline; font-family:Times New Roman, Times, serif;font-size:10pt;&gt; to simplify the test for goodwill impairment. This updated standard simplifies the subsequent measurement of goodwill and eliminates the &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;two&lt;/div&gt;-step goodwill impairment test. Under the new guidance
 an annual or interim goodwill impairment test is performed by comparing the fair value of a reporting unit with its carrying amount
 and an impairment charge is recognized for the amount by which the carrying amount exceeds the reporting unit&amp;#x2019;s fair value. The guidance also eliminates the requirements for any reporting unit with a &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;zero&lt;/div&gt; or negative carrying amount to perform a qualitative assessment and &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;two&lt;/div&gt;-step goodwill impairment test. The updated guidance is effective for our fiscal year ending &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt; September 2021 &lt;/div&gt;and interim periods within that year. Early adoption is permitted for interim or annual goodwill impairment tests performed on testing dates after &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt; January 1

 the FASB issued guidance on revenue recognition which requires that we recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration which we expect to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&amp;nbsp;We have performed a review of the requirements of the new revenue standard and are in the process of reviewing customer contracts and applying the &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;five&lt;/div&gt;-step model of this new guidance to each contract category we have identified and will compare the results to our current accounting practices. We plan to adopt this guidance on the &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;first&lt;/div&gt; day of our fiscal &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;2019&lt;/div&gt; year.  which would result in an adjustment to retained earnings for the cumulative effect
 if any
 of applying the standard to contracts in process as of the adoption date. Under this method
 we would &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;not&lt;/div&gt; restate the prior financial statements presented. Therefore

 &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=display: inline; font-family:Times New Roman, Times, serif;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;the FASB issued guidance which requires an entity to measure equity investments at fair value with changes in fair value recognized in net income 
 to use the price that would be received by a seller when measuring the fair value of financial instruments for disclosure purposes
 and which eliminates the requirement to disclose the method(s) and significant assumptions used to estimate the fair value that is required to be disclosed for financial instruments measured at amortized cost on the balance sheet.&amp;nbsp; Under present guidance
 changes in fair value of equity investments available for sale are recognized in Stockholders&amp;#x2019; Equity.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;This guidance is effective for our fiscal year ended &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt; September 2019.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/div&gt;Early adoption is &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;not&lt;/div&gt; permitted. We anticipate that the adoption of this guidance on our consolidated financial statements will &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;not&lt;/div&gt; be material. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div style= font-family: Times New Roman, Times, serif; font-size: 10pt; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div style= font-size: 10pt; margin: 0pt; text-align: left; text-indent: 36pt; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(0, 0, 0);&gt;In &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt; February 2016
 &lt;/div&gt;the FASB issued guidance on lease accounting which requires that an entity recognize most leases on its balance sheet. &lt;div style=display: inline; font-family:Times New Roman, Times, serif;font-size:10pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;The guidance retains a dual lease accounting model for purposes of income statement recognition
 continuing the distinction between what are currently known as &amp;#x201c;capital&amp;#x201d; and &amp;#x201c;operating&amp;#x201d; leases for lessees.&amp;nbsp; This guidance is effective for our fiscal year ended &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt; September 2020.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;While we continue to evaluate the effect of adopting this guidance on our consolidated financial statements and related disclosures
 we expect our operating leases
 as disclosed in Note J &amp;#x2014; Commitments and Contingencies
 will be subject to the new standard. We will recognize right-of-use assets and operating lease liabilities on our consolidated balance sheets upon adoption

 &lt;/div&gt;the FASB issued guidance on share based compensation which requires that an entity recognize all excess tax benefits and tax&lt;div style=display: inline; font-family:Times New Roman, Times, serif;font-size:10pt;&gt; deficiencies as income tax expense or benefit in the income statement as discrete items in the reporting period in which they occur. Under current guidance
 excess tax benefits are &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=display: inline; font-family:Times New Roman, Times, serif;font-size:10pt;&gt;recognized in additional paid-in capital and tax deficiencies are recognized either as an offset to accumulated excess tax benefits

 &lt;/div&gt;the FASB issued guidance to clarify the definition of a business. The updated standard provides guidance to assist entities with evaluating when a set of transferred assets and activities is a business. Under the new guidance
 an entity &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;first&lt;/div&gt; determines whether substantially all of the fair value of the gross assets acquired is concentrated in a single identifiable asset or a group of similar identifiable assets. If this threshold is met
 the set is &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;not&lt;/div&gt; a business. If it is &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;not&lt;/div&gt; met
 the entity then evaluates whether the set meets the requirements that a business include
&lt;div style=display: inline; font-family:Times New Roman, Times, serif;font-size:10pt;&gt; at a minimum
 an input and a substantive process that together significantly contribute to the ability to create outputs. The updated guidance is effective for our fiscal year ending &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt; September 2019 &lt;/div&gt;and interim periods within that year. Early adoption is permitted

 &lt;/div&gt;the FASB issued guidance&lt;div style=display: inline; font-family:Times New Roman, Times, serif;font-size:10pt;&gt; to simplify the test for goodwill impairment. This updated standard simplifies the subsequent measurement of goodwill and eliminates the &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;two&lt;/div&gt;-step goodwill impairment test. Under the new guidance
 an annual or interim goodwill impairment test is performed by comparing the fair value of a reporting unit with its carrying amount
 and an impairment charge is recognized for the amount by which the carrying amount exceeds the reporting unit&amp;#x2019;s fair value. The guidance also eliminates the requirements for any reporting unit with a &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;zero&lt;/div&gt; or negative carrying amount to perform a qualitative assessment and &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt;two&lt;/div&gt;-step goodwill impairment test. The updated guidance is effective for our fiscal year ending &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt; September 2021 &lt;/div&gt;and interim periods within that year. Early adoption is permitted for interim or annual goodwill impairment tests performed on testing dates after &lt;div style=display: inline; font-style: italic; font-weight: inherit; font-style: normal;&gt; January 1

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  


  
  


  
  


  
  


  
  


  
  


  
  


  
  


  
  


  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  


  


  


  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  













  























  
  

  
  
  

 management is required to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities
 the disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements

/**
 * Rivet Software Inc.
 *
 * @copyright Copyright (c) 2006-2011 Rivet Software
 Inc. All rights reserved.
 * Version 2.4.0.3
 *

var Show = {};
Show.LastAR = null
Show.hideAR = function(){
	Show.LastAR.style.display = 'none';
};
Show.showAR = function ( link
 id
 win ){
	if( Show.LastAR ){
		Show.hideAR();
	}
	var ref = link;
	do {
		ref = ref.nextSibling;
	} while (ref && ref.nodeName != 'TABLE');
	if (!ref || ref.nodeName != 'TABLE') {
		var tmp = win ?
			win.document.getElementById(id) :
			document.getElementById(id);
		if( tmp ){
			ref = tmp.cloneNode(true);
			ref.id = '';
			link.parentNode.appendChild(ref);
		}
	}
	if( ref ){
		ref.style.display = 'block';
		Show.LastAR = ref;
	}
};
Show.toggleNext = function( link ){
	var ref = link;
	do{
		ref = ref.nextSibling;
	}while( ref.nodeName != 'DIV' );
	if( ref.style &&
		ref.style.display &&
		ref.style.display == 'none' ){
		ref.style.display = 'block';
		if( link.textContent ){
			link.textContent = link.textContent.replace( '+'
 '-' );
		}else{
			link.innerText = link.innerText.replace( '+'
 '-' );
		}
	}else{
		ref.style.display = 'none';
		if( link.textContent ){
			link.textContent = link.textContent.replace( '-'
 '+' );
		}else{
			link.innerText = link.innerText.replace( '-'
 '+' );
		}
	}
};
